results.name: Alloclasite
results.description_short:
See also the chemically very similar Cobaltite and Glaucodot. Compare 'UM1966-01-As:CoNiS'.

Fe content is distinctly higher than that of cobaltite, and the Fe usually occupies about 25% of the (Co,Fe) site (Kingston, 1971).
results.tlform: Steel gray and fissile.
results.otheroccurrence: In calcite or quartz veins of apparently low-temperature, late-stage hydrothermal origin. Also in silicified, recrystallized metamorphic rock.
results.aboutname: For the Greek άλλος ("allos") for "other" and κλάσις ("klasis"), "to break", because its cleavage was believed to be different from marcasite.
results.morphology: Crystals are prismatic parallel <mi>[010]</mi> , to 5 mm, in columnar to radiating aggregates; commonly massive.
results.type_specimen_store: n.d.

results.name: Argentopyrite
results.description_short: Often pseudomorphed by pyrite.
results.colour: Bronze-brown, tarnishing to lead-grey to blue-gray.
results.aboutname: Named for its relationship to pyrite and silver content.
results.opticalanisotropism: Strong - deep blue to pale blue-grey
results.type_specimen_store:
Royal Ontario Museum, Toronto, Ontario, Canada (type).
National Museum of Natural History, Washington, D.C., USA (type).
results.commentcrystal: Space group P1121/n (non-standard setting). Pseudo-orthorhombic. Originally assumed to have space group Pmmn, 6.639, 11.463, 6.452 A.

results.name: Arsenopyrite
results.description_short:
Arsenopyrite Group.

Arsenopyrite is closely related to alloclasite, but is not an exact analogue, because of different As-S and S-As ordering.

Arsenopyrite may contain up to about 9 wt% Co; with higher Co contents, glaucodot will appear as a sepa...
results.otheroccurrence: High-temperature gold-quartz or tin hydrothermal veins, pegmatites, contact metamorphic rocks, gneisses, schists.
results.colour: Silver-white to steel-gray, may have a slight yellow appearance
results.aboutname: Named in 1847 by Ernst Friedrich Glocker for its composition, a contraction of the antiquated term "arsenical pyrite." Arsenopyrite was known much before 1847 and arsenopyrite, as a name, may be taken as a simple translation of "arsenkies".
results.other:
Decomposed by nitric acid with separation of arsenous acid and sulphur.

In a closed tube, at first gives a red sublimate of arsenic sulfide, then a black lustrous sublimate of metallic arsenic.  In an open tube, gives sulphurous fumes and a white sublimate of arsenous acid.
results.morphology: Flat tabular to blocky (sometimes pseudo-octahedral) to prismatic.
results.twinning: Common on {100} and {001}. Contact or penetration on {101}, on {012} trillings or cruciform.
results.opticalpleochorismdesc: White or bluish tint, faint reddish yellow
results.commentcrystal: Cell parameters from Bindi et al. (2012), using stoichiometric crystals.  Pseudo-orthorhombic, face-centred cell: ~5.7, ~6.4, ~9.6 A.

results.name: Berthierite
results.description_short: Berthierite is a relatively rare ore mineral because it is only stable over extremely narrow intervals of fO2 and fS2 (Williams-Jones and Normand, 1997).
results.otheroccurrence: Low-temperature hydrothermal veins rich in antimony and deficient in sulfur
results.colour: Dark steel-grey, often with iridescent tarnish.
results.aboutname: Named in 1827 by Wilhelm Karl von Haidinger in honor of Pierre Berthier [July 3, 1782, Nemours, Seine-et-Marne, France – August 24, 1861, France], French chemist and mineralogist at the École des Mines, and also Inspector of Mines during his career. He named a number of species including chamosite, franklinite, halloysite, and nontronite. He is well-known for his study of bauxite. The mineral <m>berthierine</m> is also named after him.
results.morphology: Prismatic on, and striated parallel to [001]. Prismatic to fibrous massive, plumose, radial; granular.
results.commentcrystal: sp. gr. Pnam

results.name: Betekhtinite
results.mindat_formula_note: Cu>>Fe. Previously given as (Cu,Fe)<sub>21</sub>Pb<sub>2</sub>S<sub>15</sub>; Krivovichev & Yakovenchuk (2017) proved this to be wrong.
results.aboutname: Named in honor of Anatolii Georgievich Betekhtin (Анатолий Георгиевич Бетехтин) (24 February (8 March) 1897, Strigino, Vologda province, Russian Empire - 20 April 1962, Moscow, USSR), mineralogist and economic geologist.
results.morphology: Needles to 2 cm in length.
results.opticalcolour: Cream, stronger yellowish cream perpendicular to elongation
results.type_specimen_store: Mineral Museum, Humboldt University, Berlin, Germany

results.name: Bornite
results.description_short:
An important copper ore, typically found as massive or disseminated metallic grains and patches in sulphide ore deposits; relatively rare as good euhedral crystals.

It has a copper-reddish colour on fresh exposures which quickly tarnishes to a pinki...
results.otheroccurrence: Common and widespread in copper ore deposits.  It also occurs in basic intrusives, in dikes, in contact metamorphic deposits, in quartz veins, and in pegmatites.
results.colour: Copper-red to pinchbeck-brown, quickly tarnishing to an iridescent purplish surface.
results.aboutname: Originally included with kupferkies in 1725 by Johann Friedrich Henckel. Later assigned various multi-word Latin names by Johan Gottschalk Wallerius in 1747 and variously further translated including "purple copper ore" and "variegated copper ore" in 1802 by Rene Just Haüy. Also called as buntkupfererz by Abraham Gottlieb Werner in 1791. Named "phillipsite" in 1832 by Wilhelm Sulpice Beudant. Renamed as bornite in 1845 by Wilhelm Karl von Haidinger in honor of Ignaz von Born (1742-1791), Austrian mineralogist and invertebrate zoologist.
results.other:
Soluble in nitric acid with separation of sulfur.

In the closed tube gives a faint sublimate of sulfur.  In the open tube, yields sulphuric acid, but gives no sublimate.

Borax bead on charcoal fuses in reducing flame to a brittle magnetic globule.  The roasted mineral gives, with fluxes, the reactions of iron and copper, and with soda, a metallic globule.
results.morphology:
Crystals rare, usually blocky with rough curved faces, pseudo-cubic, pseudo-dodecohedral and rarely pseudo-octahedral.  Forms noted: {001}, {011}, {111}, {112}, {223} and {335}.

Bornite is orthorhombic at 10 degrees K up to 275 degrees K (~ 2 degrees Celsius).
results.type_specimen_store: No designated type material.
results.commentcrystal: Various, mostly temperature-dependent supercells are known. Cell parameters are from Shu et al. (2021). Koto & Morimoto (1975) give Pbca, and a = 10.950, b = 21.862, c = 10.950 Å. High-temperature forms are cubic.

results.name: Borodaevite
results.description_short: Borodaevite is questionable as a pavonite homologue; it may correspond to a homeotypic derivative of treasurite (Ilinca & Makovicky, 1997; Moëlo et al., 2008).
results.tlform: Elongate, platy crystals, some with an angle of approx 94° between faces, or irregular grains up to 1.2 x 0.5 mm.
results.aboutname: Named in honor of Yuri Sergeevich Borodaev (Юрий Сергеевич Бородаев) (1923 - 2017), Russian mineralogist specializing in the mineralogy of ore deposits and professor at the Moscow State University. He discovered 7 new minerals.

results.type_specimen_store: A. E. Fersman Mineralogical Museum, Moscow, Russia, 87992.
results.commentcrystal: Point Group: 2/m or m.; Space Group: C2/m or Cm.

results.name: Cubanite
results.description_short:
Very sensitive to temperature, pressure and compositional variations.
When heated between 200 and 210°C, cubanite transforms irreversibly to isocubanite (Cabri et al. 1973; see also Sawada et al., 1962; Yund & Kullerud, 1966; Fleet, 1970; Dutrizac, 19...

results.other: In a closed tube it produces a sulphur sublimate.  Before the blowpipe on charcoal, gives sulphur fumes and fuses to a magnetic globule.  The roasted ore reacts for copper and iron with the fluxes; with soda on charcoal it gives a globule of metallic iron with copper.
results.morphology: Elongated, thick tabular
results.twinning: Common on {110}. Pairs, fourlings and sixlings.
results.type_specimen_store: Technische Universität, Bergakademie Freiberg, Freiberg, Germany, number 5467.

results.name: Cylindrite
results.description_short:
Cylindrite Group.

There is a relation between the cylindrical morphology and crystal structure. The latter is composite and characterizes in incommensurate modulations. There are two types of sheets, a pseudohexagonal one and a pseudotetragonal one,...
results.tlform: Crystals formed of shells of cylindrical layers.
results.aboutname: From the Greek κύλιυδροσ, a roll, in allusion to the typical cylindrical habit of the mineral.
results.morphology: Massive. Cylindrical forms separating under pressure into smooth, concentric shells. Spherically-grouped aggregates.
results.opticalpleochorismdesc: Extremely weak: Parallel to elongation gray-white, perpendicular to the elongation, darker gray-white. Stronger in oil.
results.opticalanisotropism: Distinct, gray to pale yellowish or brownish gray

results.name: Jamesonite
results.description_short:
Benavidesite-Jamesonite Series.

Easily confused with boulangerite with which it may be intergrown. As in boulangerite and, e.g., robinsonite and zinkenite, the structure contains interconnected SbS3 groups.
results.otheroccurrence: Late stage hydrothermal mineral formed at moderate to low temperature.
results.aboutname: Named in honor of Robert Jameson (11 July 1774, Leith, Scotland – 19 April 1854, Edinburgh, Scotland), naturalist and mineralogist.  He was Professor of Natural History at the University of Edinburgh for fifty years.

results.name: Marcasite
results.description_short:
Marcasite Group.

The orthorhombic polymorph of isometric (cubic) pyrite. A common natural disulfide. Compare UM1997-43-S:Fe.

Crystals common, metallic pale brass-yellow colored, tabular or pyramidal, often with curved faces and often deeply stria...
results.otheroccurrence: Most frequently found in sedimentary rocks and coal beds, as a replacement mineral forming fossils, it is a mineral of low-temperature, near-surface, environments, forming from acid solutions.  Pyrite, the more stable form of FeS^2, forms under conditions of higher temperatures and lower acidity or alkaline environments.
results.colour: Pale brass-yellow, tin-white on fresh exposures.
results.aboutname:
Early use of the word marcasite seems to have been unspecific. The word is Arabic or Moorish and was applied to pyrite and similar metallic bronze colored minerals. 

Walter Pope (1665) mentioned marcasite occurring in the mercury ores of the Idria Mine, Cividale del Friuli in the Julian Alps of Slovenia: "There are also several Marcasites and stones, which seem to have specks of Gold in them, but upon trial they say, they find none in them. These round stones are some of them very ponderous, and well impregnated with Mercury; others light, having little or none in them."

The mercury ore at Idria does contain metallic golden specks of what is now called marcasite, but it also has metallic golden pyrite. Johnathan Hill used the name marcasite in 1771, but his usage was also indiscriminate and was a term for any massive "pyrites" or "mundic". In 1845, Wilhelm Karl von Haidinger defined marcasite as the mineral is known today.
results.morphology: Crystals usually tabular on {010}, also pyramidal, faces often curved, frequently twinned; also stalactic, globular, or reniform with radiating internal structure.
results.twinning: Common on {101}, forming "swallowtail" contact twins; this may be repeated to form stellate fivelings. Less common on {011}.
results.epitaxidescription: Twinned prismatic marcasite crystals attached along pyrite octahedron edges from Rensselaer, Indiana (Brock and Slater, 1978). See also Rakovan et al. (1995).
results.opticalpleochorismdesc: Creamy white, light yellowish white, white with rose-brown tint.
results.opticalanisotropism: Strong yellow to light green to dark green
results.commentluster: Frequently iridescence obscures the luster and color

results.name: Miharaite

results.aboutname: Named in 1980 by Asahiko Sugaki, Hiromi Shima, and Arashi Kitakaze after the type locality, <l id='45343'>Mihara Mine, Okayama, Japan</l>.
results.other:
Miharaite may readily be distinguished from wittichenite: HNO3 (1:1) etches wittichenite slowly, gradually staining to a brown colour, but does not affect miharaite at all.

Miharaite is slightly stained to bluish tinges by KOH (40%). No reaction to KCN (20%), HCl (1:1), FeCl3 (20%), HgCl2(5%) and H2O2.
results.opticalcomments: Reflectance data from Choi and Imai (1983).
results.opticalanisotropism: Moderate anisotropism from grayish-blue to pinkish-brown.

Polishes poorly, easily splitting into fine needles.

Geology Museum, Kola Branch, Academy of Sciences, Apatity, Russia, 3627.
Mining Institute, St. Petersburg, Russia, 1095/1.
A.E. Fersman Mineralogical Museum, Academy of Sciences, Moscow, Russia, 73142, 73143, 73584, 73975.
results.commentcolor: Turns iridescent purple or bronze, to dull on oxidation.

results.name: Stannoidite
results.description_short: See also omariniite (formerly "Ge-stannoidite").
results.aboutname: From stannite plus Greek "eides" or Latin "oïda", like, alluding to its similarity to that mineral.
results.morphology: Massive, in veinlets, to 1 mm
results.type_specimen_store:
1) Geological Institute, University of Tokyo, Tokyo, Japan.
2) National Science Museum, Tokyo, Japan, M16183.
3) National School of Mines, Paris, France.
4) National Museum of Natural History, Washington, D.C., USA, 121005.

results.name: Sternbergite
results.description_short: A rare mineral occurring in Pinchbeck brown (yellowish brown with metallic lustre), flexible(!), mm-sized tabular crystals. It and its dimorph argentopyrite are often pseudomorphed to iron oxides which collapse to dust when poked with a needle. On the ...
results.tlform: Rose-like aggregates and globules with a drusy surface. Massive material has the habit of coarse grained mica.
results.aboutname: Named after Count Caspar Maria Sternberg (6 January 1761, Prague - 20 December 1838, Březina), botanist/entomologist/geologist/mineralogist/geognost and a founder of the National Museum of Prague (Czech Republic).
results.morphology: Thin pseudohexagonal basal plates, rosettes and fan-like aggregates.
results.opticalanisotropism: Strong, bluish and reddish to lilac, reddish brown to light green with p-urplish pink shades
results.type_specimen_store: National Museum, Prague, Czech Republic.
results.commentcrystal: Space group Ccmb (non-standard setting).

results.name: Villamanínite
results.description_short:
Pyrite Group.

See also fukuchilite.
results.tlform: Small nodular masses with a radially fibrous structure and bright spherical surfaces, to about 5 mm.
results.occurrence: Copper, cobalt, and nickel deposit in a gangue of dolomite.
results.aboutname: Named after the town of Villamanín, Spain, near the type locality of the Providencia mine. In the original description (Schoeller and Powell, 1919), the title of the paper names it villamaninite (without the diacritical mark) and in the paper as villàmaninite, which might be a typographical error as the grave accent is not used in Spanish. The current spelling of the name is villamanínite, with the diacritical matching the town name.
results.other: Soluble in nitric acid, leaving a globule of sulphur.
results.type_specimen_store: The Natural History Museum, London, England, 1919,309; 1920,7.
results.commentcrystal: Point Group: 1 or 1; pseudo 2/m 3; Space Group: P1 or P1

results.name: Pizgrischite
results.description_short: Pizgrischite belongs to the cuprobismutite series of bismuth sulfosalts but, sensu stricto, it is not a homologue of cuprobismutite.
results.tlform: Thin lead-grey blades up to 1 cm, embedded in quartz.
results.aboutname: Named after type locality.
results.type_specimen_store:
Two holotype specimens: Museum of Geology, Lausanne (MGL), Switzerland. Sample MGL 58622 (isolated crystals) and sample MGL 53660 (polished
section).
Cotype: British Museum of Natural History, London, England.

results.name: Kupčíkite
results.description_short: Structurally closely related to cuprobismutite and hodrušite.
results.tlform: Elongated grains to 1 mm.
results.occurrence: Sulphosalt bearing quartz veins, hosted by paleozoic amphibolites, hornblendites and granite gneisses.
results.aboutname: Named in honor of Vladimir Kupčík (1934-1990), former Professor of Crystallography in the universities of Göttingen, Germany and Bratislava, Slovak Republic.  It is pronounced k-ou-p-tch-ee-kite.
results.opticalpleochorismdesc:
Weak in air, white with bluish tints, and enhanced in
oil.
results.opticalanisotropism: Moderate in air and strong in oil.  The rotation tints between polars are dark bluish gray to yellowish brown for the most anisotropic grains.
results.opticalbireflectance: Perceptible in air, and moderate in oil
results.type_specimen_store:
Holotype: The Geological Institute and Geological Museum, University of
Copenhagen, Denmark.
Cotype: The Mineralogical Institute, University of Salzburg, Austria (catalogue no. 14933).

results.name: Pautovite
results.description_short: An unusual caesium sulphide mineral that occurs as small elongated black aggregates. The only currently known mineral combining Cs and S. The second Cs-Fe mineral after caesiumpharmacosiderite.
results.tlform: Crude prismatic to acicular crystals up to 120 microns in length and 15 microns thick, in subparallel overgrowths on belovite-(Ce).
results.aboutname: Named in honour of Leonid Anatolyevich Pautov (Леонид Анатольевич Паутов) (b. 1958), A.E. Fersman Museum, Moscow, Russia, in recognition of his studies of minerals by physical methods, the mineralogy of alkaline pegmatites, and the mineralogy of cesium.
results.opticalpleochorismdesc: Greyish white to grey with a slight pinkish tint.
results.opticalcomments: On the section perpendicular to the crystal elongation, pautovite is isotropic.
results.opticalanisotropism: Strong, dark grey to hardly noticeable pale brownish grey
results.type_specimen_store: A.E. Fersman Mineralogical Museum, Russian Academy of Sciences, Moscow, Russia (# 3168/1).

results.name: Coiraite
results.description_short: The As analogue of Franckeite.
results.tlform: very dense, earthy and fine-grained aggregates with a distinct colloform texture
results.occurrence: Polymetallic hydrotermal veins in Ordovician sediments of the Acoyte Formation
results.cleavage: parallel to a basal plane - synthetic
results.aboutname: Named after Beatriz Lydia Coira (born 1941), Professor of Petrology at the University of Jujuy, NW Argentina, for her outstanding research on volcanism, regional geology and its relation to ore-deposit formation in Argentina.
results.opticalanisotropism: moderately anisotropic in oil and the rotation tints are brown to bluish-grey
results.opticalbireflectance: very weak in air and oil
results.type_specimen_store: Department of Materials Engineering and Physics, University of Salzburg, Austria, registered under catalogue numbers 14943-14946, in the reference collections of the Natural History Museum, London, UK (BM 2008, 47), the Landesmuseum Joanneum, Graz, Styria
results.commentcrystal: has two monoclinic sub-cells, Q (pseudotetragonal) and H (pseudohexagonal). Above data is for Q cell.

results.name: Chenguodaite
results.description_short: Compare 'UM1989-18-S:AgFeTe'.
results.tlform: xenomorphic rounded or irregular shapes with the grain size 5―70 μm
results.aboutname: Named in honor of Chen Guoda (陈国达) (22 January 1912, Xinhui County, Guangdong Province, China - 7 April 2004, Changsha, Hunan province, China), geologist, professor, and founder of Diwa-Geodepression theory of tectonics.
results.type_specimen_store: Chinese Geological Museum, the catalogue number is M10487
results.commentcrystal: point Group n.d.; Space Group n.d.

results.name: Omariniite
results.description_short: The Ge analogue of stannoidite. Chemically somewhat similar to zincobriartite, renierite, and briartite.  X-ray single-crystal studies (R1 = 0.023) revealed the structure to be a sphalerite derivative identical to that of stannoidite (Bindi et al. 2017).
results.tlform: Seams in ore rarely exceeds 60 μm.
results.occurrence: In bornite-chalcocite-rich ores of the Capillitas epithermal deposit
results.cleavage: Not observed in the polished sections
results.parting: Not observed in the polished sections
results.aboutname: Named in honor of Dr. Ricardo Héctor Omarini (17 March 1946, Córdoba, Argentina - 28 June 2015), Professor at the University of Salta, for his numerous contributions to the geology of Argentina.
results.opticalanisotropism: Distinctly, with rotation tints varying between brownish-orange and greenish-brown.
results.type_specimen_store: Collections of the Systematic Reference Series of the National Mineral Collection of Canada, Geological Survey of Canada, Ottawa, Ontario, Canada (catalogue number NMCC 68096)

results.name: Zolenskyite
results.description_short: The Fe (or FeCr2) analogue of brezinaite and a dimorph of daubréelite.
results.tlform: Euhedral to subhedral crystals 10-20 microns.
results.aboutname: Named in honor of Michael E. Zolensky (b. 1955), planetary scientist with NASA, for his contributions to research on extraterrestrial materials, including enstatite chondrites. He is an expert on meteoritic mineralogy, petrology and geochemistry, space weathering, and the primitive mineralogy of comets. He is a past president of The Meteoritical Society and was awarded the 2020 Leonard Medal. The minor planet 6030/Zolensky is also named in his honor.
results.type_specimen_store: Type material is deposited in the meteorite collection of the Division of Geological and Planetary Sciences, California Institute of Technology, 1200 East California Boulevard, Pasadena, CA 91125, USA, catalogue numbers ICM1 and ICM3.
results.commentcrystal: zolenskyite has the C2/m CrNb2Se4-Cr3S4-type structure of synthetic FeCr2S4

results.name: Ferrofettelite
results.description_short: The Fe analogue of fettelite. Chemically related to kenoargentotennantite-(Fe) and 'Unnamed (Fe-analogue of Argentotennantite-(Zn))'.
results.tlform: Anhedral to subhedral flakes and grains up to 80 μm.
results.aboutname: The mineral is the Fe-dominant analogue of fettelite.
results.type_specimen_store: Collections of the University of Arizona Gem and Mineral Museum, 115 N Church Ave., Tucson, AZ 85701, USA, catalogue number 22716.

results.name: Hanswilkeite
results.description_short: The discovery of KFeS2, the first natural potassium-bearing dithioferrate: the sulfosalt of the [FeS2]- anion where, in contrast to other natural K-Fe sulfides, all iron is comprised by Fe3+. The synthetic analogue of the reported new mineral, hanswilk...
results.tlform: It forms single-crystal grains up to 1 mm in size, isometric to lath-like, often intergrown with a less-common rasvumite, KFe2S3.
results.occurrence: The mineral occurs in sulfide-calcite assemblages confined to black-colored calcite-spurrite marbles
results.cleavage: Moderate cleavage was observed along the c-axis
results.aboutname: The new mineral is named in honour of Dr. Hans-Jürgen Wilke (1925-2014), the German mineral collector, for his contributions to popularisation of mineralogy.
results.other: The Raman spectrum contains the following bands (cm-1 ): 379, 357 (stretching vibrations Fe-S in FeS4 tetrahedra); 289 (bending modes in FeS4 tetrahedra); 236, 167, 131 and 124 (lattice modes).
results.type_specimen_store: Type material is deposited in the collections of the Fers- man Mineralogical Museum, Russian Academy of Sciences, Leninskiy Prospekt 18-2, Moscow 119071, Russia, registration number 5862/1
results.specdispm: Hanswilkeite, while exposed onto the sample surface at room humidity, becomes rusty within 1-2 days.

results.name: Ginelfite
results.description_short: New structure type. Chemically similar to baiamareite.
results.type_specimen_store: collections of( 1) the Museo di Storia Naturale, Università di Pisa, Via Roma 79, Calci (PI), Italy, catalogue number 20023, and (2) the Department of Mineralogy and Petrology, National Museum, Cirkusová 1740, 193 00 Prague 9, Czech Republic, catalogue number P1P 31/2022

results.name: Ferrodimolybdenite
results.description_short:
Not unique in terms of chemical combination (compare maikainite).

Known synthetic analogue.
results.tlform: platy crystals with dimensions ranging from 3×100 µm to 20×40 µm.
results.occurrence: was discovered in a differentiated sulfide nodule composed of troilite and pentlandite parts. The nodule was detected in the central zone of a diopside-anorthite-tridymite oval paralava body, approximately 30 metres in diameter, within the pyrometamorphic Hatrurim Complex in Daba-Siwaqa, Jordan.
results.cleavage: cleavage in three directions: perfect on {001}, good on {100} and poor on {010}
results.aboutname: The mineral name ferrodimolybdenite is derived from its composition and structure: “ferro” refers to Fe2+, while “di+molybdenite” indicates the presence of two MoS2 layers.
results.opticalcolour: grey to light grey with a bluish tinge
results.type_specimen_store:
collections of the Fersman Mineralogical Museum, Russian
Academy of Sciences, Leninskiy Prospekt 18-2, Moscow 115162, Russia, registration number 6005/1

results.name: Baiamareite
results.description_short: The Fe analogue of uchucchacuaite. As such, it may also be grouped in the andorite series. Chemically comparable with ginelfite.
results.aboutname: For the famous Baia Mare mining district, NW Romania, which comprises world-class polymetallic ore deposits.
results.type_specimen_store: Collection of the Mineralogisch-Petrographische Abteilung, Naturhistorisches Museum, Burgring 7, A-1010 Wien, Austria, catalogue number NHMW-MIN-O2598.
results.commentcrystal: the space group is P2<sub>1</sub>/n
